And if you truly wish to assist and have ample resources, we could greatly use your help in building new homes for our growing families. But be aware, we are humble folk with little wealth, and cannot offer much in the way of payment.

You scan the settlement, noting what needs fixing—there’s always something. You start with a sagging fence or weakened wall, replacing worn materials and securing gaps to maintain safety. Next, you repair a damaged roof, weaving in new materials and reinforcing the structure to withstand harsh weather. With each repair, the settlement feels more secure, and the residents show their appreciation as their homes and buildings are made safer by your skilled hands.

You begin by sweeping the paths, clearing away dust and leaves to make the village look tidy. Next, you head to the fields, where you help gather ripe crops, carefully bundling them for storage, and tend to the animals by feeding them and ensuring their pens are secure. Afterward, you make several trips to the well, fetching water to fill the barrels for daily use. Finally, you stack firewood neatly beside the cottages, preparing for the colder nights ahead.

Indeed, there is work to be done... There are various tasks around the castle that should not take long. We are always in need of skilled hands for repairs and maintenance. You could also lend a hand with the current construction projects within the walls.

You step into the bustling construction site within the grounds, where a new structure is already taking shape. Workers are busy hauling materials and assembling the framework, but much remains to be done. You join in, helping to reinforce the walls and support the ongoing work, ensuring everything is built sturdy and secure. As you contribute your skills, the project progresses swiftly, and the workers nod in appreciation for your assistance in this important addition to the settlement.

You arrive at the settlement and are quickly directed to the site where new structures are needed to accommodate the growing population. The foundation has been laid, but much work remains. You begin by setting the wooden beams for the framework, ensuring each one is sturdy and well-placed. As the walls rise, you carefully fit the timber together, building strong support for the roof. Once the structure is sound, you assist in securing the roof, whether it be thatched with straw or covered in tiles, ensuring it is tightly woven to keep the elements out. With each step, the new buildings take shape, and the people show their gratitude as their community grows, offering shelter and space to those in need.

I have questions about your faith. May I ask them?
Of course, my child. What troubles your heart?
You may ask, for it is my duty to guide those who wish to learn the truth.
Speak freely, and I shall do my best to answer with wisdom and faith.

If your heart is sincere, I will answer. What do you seek to know?

I preach the ancient wisdom of our fathers, the sacred connection between the living world and the spirits that dwell within it. Our path is not simply a religion, but a way of life that honors the great powers of nature - the thunder of Perkūnas, the nurturing earth of Žemyna, the wisdom of Medeinė who watches over the forests.\r\nWe teach that every tree has a spirit, every river a guardian, every stone a memory. Our people do not worship in closed halls of stone, but under the open sky, where the wind carries the breath of our ancestors. We respect the cycles of life - the birth of spring, the abundance of summer, the harvest of autumn, and the quiet sleep of winter.

I preach the eternal word of God, the path of salvation through Jesus Christ. Our mission is to spread the Gospel, to bring light to those living in darkness, and to guide souls toward divine grace and eternal life.\r\nWe teach that mankind is born in sin, but through Christ's mercy, we can be redeemed. Every soul is precious in God's eyes, and our purpose is to bring people closer to Him through faith, prayer, and adherence to the holy scriptures.

I preach the fullness of divine truth, preserved unchanged since the Apostles. Our faith is not merely a doctrine, but a living tradition that connects us directly to Christ. We do not seek to interpret scriptures through modern lenses, but to live as closely as possible to the original teachings.\r\nOur worship is a mystical journey where heaven and earth meet. Every liturgy is a sacred moment where the Eucharist becomes the body and blood of Christ. We do not simply remember - we participate in the eternal sacrifice. Our churches are gateways between the visible and invisible worlds.

Our preaching is about balance. Balance between humans and nature, between the seen and unseen worlds. We remind our people that we are not masters of the earth, but part of its great web. We seek harmony through ritual, through offerings, through understanding the subtle threads that connect all living things.\r\nWhen we make sacrifice, it is not out of fear, but out of respect and gratitude. When we pray, we do not beg, but communicate. Our gods are not distant rulers, but companions on our journey, as close as the ground beneath our feet and the sky above our heads.

Our preaching focuses on love, forgiveness, and the promise of salvation. We call upon sinners to repent, to turn away from worldly temptations, and to embrace the holy sacraments. Baptism, confession, and the Eucharist are powerful channels of divine grace.\r\nWe are soldiers of God, fighting against spiritual darkness. Our ultimate goal is not comfort in this temporary world, but eternal salvation in the presence of God. Every sermon, every prayer is a step toward that divine promise.

We teach salvation as a profound journey of theosis - becoming like God through divine grace. Prayer is not just speaking, but a deep spiritual practice of transformation. Our icons are windows into divine reality, channels of God's uncreated light.\r\nOur tradition is rich with mysticism - we seek to experience God directly, not just understand Him intellectually. We preserve the ancient wisdom, unbroken and pure, a living path of spiritual growth.
What are your thoughts about Baltic Paganism?
How do you view the beliefs and practices of Catholicism?
Can you share your thoughts on the Orthodoxy?

Baltic Paganism is the worship of false gods, idols, and spirits that deceive the soul and lead men away from the true path of salvation. These practices are rooted in darkness and ignorance, keeping people from the light of Christ and eternal life. It is our sacred duty to bring these people to the one true God, for only through Christ can their souls be saved.

Paganism is a rebellion against God and His Church. The Lord has sent His servants to bring you out of the darkness and into the light of salvation. To resist this is to resist God's will. Accept baptism and the teachings of Christ, and you will find peace and forgiveness. Persist in pagan ways, and you risk both your soul and the judgment of those sent by God to bring order to these lands.

Baltic Paganism seeks to explain the mysteries of the world, but it falls short of the full truth. You honor the forces of nature, but do you not wonder who created these forces? Who gave life to the forests, strength to the winds, and light to the sun? It is the Lord God, the Creator of Heaven and Earth. To worship nature is to worship the creation rather than the Creator. Turn your hearts to Him, and you will find eternal truth and salvation.

Baltic paganism binds its followers to darkness and falsehood. By worshiping false gods, they turn away from the one true God and risk their souls to eternal damnation. The time will come when every knee shall bow and every tongue confess the Lord Jesus Christ.

Your devotion to the forces of nature shows that you seek the divine, but you are like a traveler lost in the forest, seeing only the shadows of the truth. The spirits and gods you worship are but creations of the one true God, who sent His Son, Jesus Christ, to bring salvation to all people. Turn to Him, for He is the Creator of all that you hold sacred.

Christianity is the path of foreigners who seek to change what the gods of our ancestors have ordained. They bring new gods and claim them higher than ours, yet our gods have stood with us in the forests, in the fields, and in battle since the dawn of time. Why should we abandon them for distant promises?

Catholicism shares the light of Christ, but it has strayed from the unity of the true Church. By elevating the Pope above all bishops and changing the sacred Creed, they have created divisions in Christendom. Yet, they remain our brothers in faith, and we must pray for their return to the path of the Apostles, so that the Church may once again be united as one body in Christ.

The Orthodox seem much like the Catholics, though their prayers and ways differ. They carry their icons and bow to their god, but do they not see the spirits that dwell in the earth beneath their feet? Perhaps their god is wise, but wisdom comes also from honoring the land and the spirits that have guided us for generations.

The Orthodox Church has allowed pride and worldly politics to divide it from the unity of Christ’s Church. Its leaders, especially in Constantinople, have placed earthly power above divine authority, rejecting the Holy Father in Rome. This schism weakens all Christendom, and we must strive to bring the Orthodox back into communion with the Church to stand united against threats to the faith.
It is my honor to share what I know. May your journey be filled with wisdom.
Very well. I am here if you have more questions in the future.

The name Upytė was first mentioned in 1254 in a Livonian chronicle dealing with the divisions of the Upmala region. Upytė had a wooden castle built on an island which later became a hillfort when Lake Vešeta was drained. The castle was an important northern defence post against numerous incursions of the Livonian Order.

In the 13th century, Gdańsk stood as a prosperous Baltic port city and trading center under the rule of Pomeranian dukes, with its wooden and earthen fortifications protecting the bustling settlement. The city's strategic location at the mouth of the Vistula River made it a crucial meeting point for merchants from across the Baltic and Central Europe, where Slavic traders mingled with German merchants and other seafarers in its growing harbor district.

In the 13th century, Plock served as one of the most significant centers of Masovia, functioning both as a major ecclesiastical seat with its impressive cathedral and as a crucial political center for the Masovian dukes. The city's strategic location on the high bank of the Vistula River enhanced its importance as a trade hub, while its strong fortifications, including a castle on the hill, helped protect it during the tumultuous period of feudal divisions in medieval Poland.

The Balts, who live along the southeastern Baltic Sea, have their own languages, unique cultural practices, and pagan beliefs. They organize themselves into tribes, each led by a chieftain, maintaining independence while sharing a common cultural and religious bond.
Northern Crusaders embarked on military campaigns to Christianize the Baltic peoples, leading to significant cultural and territorial changes in the region.

Rus' culture, notable in Eastern Europe, blends Slavic traditions with influences from neighboring regions. It encompasses city-states like Kiev, Novgorod, and Vladimir, each governed by a prince. The society is hierarchically structured with princes, nobles, free peasants, and servants. Predominantly Eastern Orthodox since Prince Vladimir's Christianization in 988, Rus' culture aligns closely with Byzantium, contrasting with Western Catholic and Baltic pagan customs.

Finno-Ugric Old-Estonian culture is a robust, forest-dwelling society with a deep reverence for nature, practicing ancient animistic rituals and speaking a unique Finno-Ugric language, expert in guerrilla warfare and skilled in crafting from natural materials, reflecting their symbiotic relationship with the dense woodlands of northeastern Europe.
In the 13th century, Danish Crusaders, led by King Valdemar II, conquered maritime Estonia, establishing Danish rule as part of the broader Northern Crusades.

I am balt. But for 20 years, I fought for the teutons. Indeed, most balts my age learned their trade in the army. We saw no dishonor in it. They fed us well, they paid us well, they respected our courage.

But my lord is gone - died in the battle. And since Mindaugas became king, well, he's gotten the young to think that to fight for the teutons is treason. Treason to what? 'Lithuania'? There is no Lithuania. Never has been. Just a bunch of quarreling chieftains, who'll steal your cows as soon as you turn your back on them.
Anyway, well, I've had it with narrow escapes from charging knights, and I'm going to seek work in a more professional force.

I am balt by birth but I served with the teutons. Many of us did. A brave lord, a captain who cares for his men... What does it matter in which language your oath of fealty is given, as long as you honor it?

I am the prince of horsethieves! I have stolen teuton mares from amid the tents and ridden them across the desert under the moon, I have taken rus stallions from their paddocks, the sturdy ponies of the polacks, and the steady geldings of the mongol lancers. But, I'll be the first to admit, it is risky work, so sometimes I do other jobs.

My family was not one of the greatest clans of the Prussians, but neither are we among the poorest. When I came of age, my family sent me to join the Wolfskins. You may have heard of this tradition - for three years we live in the woods and do not eat cooked meat, wear spun cloth, or sleep under a roof, and according to the law we are beasts, not bound by the laws of men.

Aye, once I made a fine living, in the Kievan Rus, stopping merchants on the roads and asking 'em for a bit of change. But there was a lass there, beautiful as the moon and just as cold, and she was my undoing. Courted by an local chieftain but I thought, I can do better than that, with my takings, and I brought her the pick of the rings and finery and asked her to pass the evening with me.

She agreed, eagerly enough! There was wine and talk, but too much wine, and I slept off. Then woke in the morning, I did, and hooves were clattering outside and up comes the chieftain and a file of horsemen, and away they took me to the town to be hanged.

My uncle - he had a great herd of cows, and in the Semogitian upcountry that is only kind of wealth we value. But they were taken by his chief herdsman, a man we trusted. So we took up spears to get them back, but my uncle was now poor, but the thief had many kinsmen. Having nothing else to lose, my uncle ordered that even the women of our family take up spears and ride out to fight, and so we did.

I'm an engineer. Most of us learned our trade and got our contacts through the army. It was a good system: it was the master's money, so the master's servants kept a close eye on us. But as everyone knows, the Grand Master ran out of money. The governors are in charge of fortifications now, and all they have to go on is the say-so of other engineers.
I'm an engineer, with an army training. I'm sure by now you've met a few of us around, and know a bit about what we can do.
See, there's a lot of tales about me, and only some of them are true. The rus call me by one name, the balts by another.
My father was a rider in the east. We had a small estate to pay for his horse and armor. I was raised to take his place on the rider's troop rosters when he came of age.

But the Mongols overran us, and he was slain, and our land was taken. Its revenues now belong to some tarkhan. Alas, the Kingdom has little land to grant today, even to trained cavalrymen like myself who wish to serve. And horses are expensive.

You may call it pride, but I do not wish to enlist as a foot soldier. So I work here in town, for merchants, for pay, a hired sword. All I can say is that I hope one day to purchase the land I need to serve our master, whoever sits in the throne, as my father did.
A cavalier of the kingdom doing errands for traders! The shame of it!
I'm a former rider. Our skills, and our honor, needs no further introduction. But I was unable to afford my horse and armor, so I took work with merchants, as a hired sword.

I'm a soldier by trade. I've served in the army for 20 years. Once upon a time they were worthy of being called 'soldier.' We served together for years, and we'd die rather than see our standards falter or fall.
But our general led us into an ambush. You may have heard that story. I was laid up sick at the time. But a lot of my comrades didn't come back, and things were never the same afterward.

After so-called reforms, they try to maintain an army on the cheap, letting the rich run the show out of their own pocket. No wonder the whole thing's collapsed into a bunch of squabbling factions and we're mocked by the barbarians we used to rule.

I'm a soldier. How we came to this sorry state is a sad tale that you've no doubt heard already from my comrades. But I'm sure you're familiar with our mettle in battle, and our skill at turning youths into soldiers.

You may have heard of Ladimos the Red. He preached that the Heavens were getting ready to unload their wrath on landowners and merchant, that we had to drive them out and live pure lives and we'd be rewarded with a Pure Ruler, come down from the skies. This was some 10 years ago. Well, a lot of us ran off to follow him, some of us believed him and some of us had debts and some just wanted to take a lick at those that oppressed us.

We built a great temple in the back country, out in the bush, called it the Kingdom of Truth. We whipped two detachments sent to track us down. But Ladimos died, 'Called up to Heaven' he said on his deathbed, and then we lost our way a bit. We needed food and we needed money, so our chiefs started collecting 'taxes' from the villages below. Some started taking money from lords and merchants for protection of caravans. And those who grumbled - well, they started turning up dead in the dry streambeds.

My family had debts, so I signed up to be a soldier. I guess I always liked men's work more than women's work. The army took hill women as scouts but I was never the hidey-sneaky type. So I did what I did to be in the spear line.
I dressed as a man to serve in the army. There are many of us who've done that, believe it or not. You've probably met one of us before, even if you didn't know it.

My father was a merchant in Berlin. We lived in a rich house, with many servants. I wanted for nothing. Our neighbor was a moneylender, who specialized in loans to the guard. That turned out to be a bad neighborhood in which to live, when the riots came.

Far back as I remember, I was living on the streets of Vienna with a bunch of other dirty, barefoot scrogs. A group of men in our alley, they called themselves the Centaurs, I guess they took a liking to me. Gave me special errands to run from them - started with picking pockets, ended with sticking knives into their enemies. Back then I'd do anything for a handful of figs and cheese and a pat on the head.
Then came the day that Vienna burned, and everyone was out looting and robbing, and that was my chance. Lifted a bag of silver from the Centaurs' stash and lit out on the road.

I was an orphan, you see. Worked for a gang, as our kind must so often do. Did their foul work for them. But they perished in a siege, and I decided to strike out on my own, see what this fine land could offer me.
I'm a surgeon. I trained at the academy in Prague. I had many rich and influential patients in the town. I thought I was well shielded from the intrigues and dangers of the world.

But one day I was contacted by an agent of the Bureau of Barbarian Affairs. I do not know how well you know them. At first they wanted small harmless details about my patients. To do so was a violation of my oath, but I was anxious to have the favor of the Bureau. But soon they began to call on me for more and more.

One time they came at midnight - they had a man who plotted against the King, they said, and they needed a confession, and wished me to use my art to elicit that confession. If I refused, they said, they would disclose our relationship to my patients - I would be ruined. I went with them, to my shame, and what I was asked to do to that man's body -- I shall not repeat it.

I was a surgeon, trained at the academy. But my home and infirmary were burned in a bout of unrest, and now I must wander the world a bit. There are many of us out there, you know, forced to make what living we can.

My father was a cavalry man. Alas, he died in battle against the Mongols, and I was placed under the local archon's guardianship. He had eyes for my father's estate, modest as it was, so he arranged for me to be married to his cousin.

I fled a bad marriage. There are many like me; I meet them in every tavern. I am lucky in that my father was a cavalry man, and taught me to ride and fight before he died, and I suppose that's how I must make a living.
I was an herbalist in a village in the north. But our home was raided, and I've been forced to wander in search of work. There are many like me on the roads of Kievan Rus.

Started in the Prince's guard. I found that I was the only real warrior among them. They were all about marching here and there in their pretty uniforms, not pulling sword from scabbard for months on end. I told them what I thought, and my captain told me to keep my mouth shut or leave. So I left.

Then I joined the gang. They spent most of their time hunkering behind their shields. Ha! Me, I'd wade into the midst of the enemy, dealing out death right and left - and, well, all they had to say afterward was 'Why didn't you keep ranks?'
Let me tell you friend, I'm hard. I've fought with the mercenaries worth their salt, I've been with them. Others may tell you've they've done what I've done, but I'm the real thing.
Aye - you've heard about the death of the last Prince?

I'll tell you - what most people believe is a pack of lies. I was in the Prince's guard. We took our discipline seriously; we were proud of it. Then the riots happened. What I saw in Kyiv.. Even now it makes me feel ashamed.
I have heard about the riots in Kyiv. It was an ugly thing all round.
The guard didn't kill the Prince? Funny, that's not what the witnesses said.

I was part of the old Prince's Guard. But the people turned on us after his death, and attacked us. Maybe you've heard the story before. There's a whole lot of us, spat out into the world by the ungrateful rus.

We rus have a tradition. If two people have a dispute, and there's no witnesses, so it all comes down to one man's word against another's, then we let them settle it with swords. If one man doesn't like to fight, he can hire someone else to do the fighting. That's how it works with us. Probably other people do the same, because it's a good tradition.
My story? It’s one of hunger, cold nights, and the greed of men that left me with nothing.

I grew up in a small hut near the forest. My father hunted for what he could, but the seasons were cruel, and we were always hungry. The chieftain of our tribe demanded more tribute each year, and when we had no more grain to give, he took our only goat.

My mother tried to reason with him, but they laughed at us. That night, a sickness took her, and I buried her with my bare hands. My father followed soon after, leaving me alone. The forest became my home, and the shadows my only friends.

I learned to steal from the traders who passed through. A bit of bread here, a strip of dried meat there. I was quick and quiet, and for a while, I survived. But life in the woods is harsh, and I learned that even the smallest mistake could be deadly.
Survival demands a certain cruelty. Who could blame you?
Living as a thief will catch up with you eventually.

I’ve had enough of living in the shadows. There’s no future for a girl like me out there. So now, I wander, hoping to find something better, something that doesn’t end in a shallow grave beneath the trees.

I’ve lived in the woods for as long as I can remember, surviving by stealing what I could. But that life wears you down, and I’m looking for a way out. Perhaps I’ll find it in the towns or on the roads.
My story? You could say bad luck followed me like a hungry wolf.

My father was the best hunter in our village. He could track deer through the thickest forests and bring down wolves with a single arrow. I always thought I’d follow in his footsteps, but fate had other plans.

One winter, the game disappeared, as if the forest itself had swallowed them up. My father went out deeper into the woods, searching for anything that could fill our bellies. He never came back. They say the cold took him, or maybe worse.

Left with nothing but his old bow and a few arrows, I tried to make a living. But the forest is a cruel place for a boy alone. I lost more than I gained, and soon, hunger gnawed at me just as it had at my father.
It sounds like you've had to struggle for every scrap.
Bad luck or not, the forest doesn’t forgive mistakes.
I can’t keep living like this, chasing shadows and hoping for a break. I came to the town, thinking maybe there’s work here, something that doesn’t involve freezing to death alone in the woods.

I grew up as a hunter’s son, but the forest hasn’t been kind. My father is gone, and I’ve been struggling to survive on my own. Now I’m looking for another way, hoping the town might offer me a chance.
My story? It’s the tale of a young girl trying to survive in a world that cares little for the weak.

My family was poor, and the winters were long. We barely scraped by, tending to our sheep, hoping the wool they provided would be enough to feed us. My father died when I was young, and my mother was too ill to work, so the burden fell on me.

I walked to the market every week, a basket full of wool on my back. The merchants were cruel, always driving the price down, knowing I had no choice but to accept. Still, it was all we had. Every coin I earned went to keep us alive, but it was never enough.

One day, my mother passed away, and with her, the last bit of hope I had. I was alone, with nothing but a few ragged clothes and the knowledge that I had to fend for myself. So I kept going, selling what little I could, but it became harder and harder to make ends meet.
It’s a harsh world for those without means. You did what you had to do.
Selling wool might have kept you alive, but it won’t get you far.

I couldn’t live like that forever. The market life, the constant hunger, the endless struggle... it broke me. So I left. Now I wander, searching for something better, something that doesn’t involve counting every last coin to survive.
I used to sell wool at the market, trying to keep my family fed. But that life is behind me now. I’m searching for a new path, one that doesn’t involve begging for scraps from greedy merchants.
My story? It’s not one of noble birth or riches. I never knew my parents, only the cold of the sewers.

I was born in the filth of the city streets, or so I’m told. I never knew my mother or father. I grew up with the rats, scavenging what I could from the trash and muck. When the hunger became too much, I learned to trap the very creatures I shared my home with.

Life in the sewers isn’t for the faint of heart. It’s dark, cold, and filled with things that would rather see you dead. But I learned to survive. I hunted rats for food, stole scraps from the market stalls above, and kept to the shadows, always one step ahead of the guards.

I’ve never known kindness, only the fight to stay alive. The sewers were my home, but they were also my prison. I knew I couldn’t live like that forever. So I made my way out, desperate for something better, though I have no idea where to start.
Surviving in the sewers takes more strength than many would realize.
Living like that, it’s a wonder you made it this far.
I’m done with the sewers. The filth, the hunger, the endless struggle... it’s no life for anyone. Now I wander, hoping to find a better path, one that doesn’t lead back to the gutter.
I grew up in the sewers, surviving on whatever I could find. It wasn’t much of a life, so I left, hoping to find something better above the streets.
My story? It’s one of poverty, desperation, and tears over lost locks of hair.

We were always poor. My mother did what she could to keep us fed, but there was never enough. One day, she told me we had no choice. She took her knife and cut my hair, saying it could be sold to buy food. I cried until my eyes were sore, but that didn’t bring my hair back.

The town’s merchant paid a few coins for my hair, and we ate that night, but I felt like a piece of me was taken with those locks. My mother said I should be proud that I helped keep us alive, but I couldn’t shake the feeling of loss. Every time I touched my head, I was reminded of how little we had.

I never let my hair grow long again. The pain of losing it once was enough, and I couldn’t bear to have it happen again. So I kept it short, and we struggled on, always one step away from starvation. Life wasn’t kind to us, and in the end, I had to leave, hoping to find a better life somewhere else.
You did what you had to do. Survival demands sacrifices.
Losing your hair for a few coins... that must have been hard to bear.
I couldn’t stay. The pain of that life weighed on me every day. So I left. Now I wander, searching for something more, something that doesn’t involve selling parts of myself just to survive.
I grew up poor, so poor that my mother cut my hair and sold it to buy food. We struggled, and I couldn’t stay in that life. Now I’m looking for a way out, a chance at something better.
My story? It’s the smell of saltwater and fish guts, following me wherever I go.

I grew up on the sea, helping my father on his fishing boat. We lived for the catch, and every day I was surrounded by fish—alive, dead, or rotting in the sun. The sea fed us, but it also left its mark. No matter how much I scrubbed, the smell never went away.

The other villagers kept their distance. They called me ‘Fish-boy’ and wrinkled their noses whenever I walked by. I didn’t mind at first—after all, fishing was all I knew. But as I grew older, the isolation started to wear on me. I was tired of being the one who always smelled like the sea.

Even when I left the boat behind, the smell stayed with me. It clung to my skin, my clothes... people could sense it from across the room. No one wanted to be near me. So I left the village, hoping to find a place where I could start fresh, away from the stench of fish and salt.
A life on the sea might toughen you up, but I suppose the smell is a part of that.
Carrying the scent of the sea everywhere... I can see why that would be hard.
I couldn’t stay there any longer. I’ve had enough of the fish, the sea, and the loneliness. Now I wander, looking for a place where people don’t wrinkle their noses at me before I even speak.

I spent my life on a fishing boat, surrounded by the smell of fish and saltwater. It never left me, and neither did the stares from others. Now I’m searching for a place where I can be free of that past.
My story? I’m the daughter of nobility—or at least, I believe I am. That life was taken from me.

I grew up in a grand castle, or so my parents said. They told me we were of noble blood, that our line was ancient and respected. I believed them. I spent my days in the hallways of that castle, dreaming of the life that noble birthright promised me.

But those dreams turned to ash. One night, men in iron armor came—they set our castle ablaze. I remember the flames climbing higher, consuming everything. My parents told me to run, and so I did. I escaped into the forest, the last thing I saw was the man standing in the doorway as the castle crumbled behind him.

In the forest, I was alone. I had no one, nothing. I survived by eating mushrooms and berries, drinking from streams, and hiding from the beasts of the woods. Somehow, I lived, though I’m not sure how. But I could never shake the feeling that my noble blood would protect me, even when there was nothing left of that life.
To survive the loss of everything... it takes strength, noble or not.
A noble birth means little when you’re alone in the woods.
I’ve wandered for so long now, leaving the forest behind, but the memories still follow me. I’m searching for a way to reclaim what I lost—or maybe to find out if it was ever real to begin with.
I grew up believing I was a noble, living in a grand castle. But that life was burned away by enemies. I survived in the forest, but now I wander, searching for a way back to the life I lost.
My story? It’s one of fire, sweat, and chains. I spent my youth as a slave, chained to the blacksmith's forge.

I was born into servitude, or so it feels. From a young age, I was forced to work the bellows and carry heavy iron bars for the blacksmith in the castle. The heat from the furnace was unbearable, and the smell of burning metal and sweat never left me. My back is still sore from all the beatings I took when I wasn’t fast enough.

Every day was the same—slaving away in the forge, knowing that I’d never be free. My hands became calloused, and my lungs burned from the constant smoke. The blacksmith was a cruel master, quick with his fists and slow with mercy. I knew I couldn’t live that life forever.

One night, after another beating left me too weak to stand, I decided I’d had enough. I waited until the castle was quiet, and then I ran. I ran until my legs couldn’t carry me anymore, and then I hid. I knew that if they found me, they’d drag me back to the forge, but anything was better than that furnace.
To escape a life of servitude takes courage. You must have been desperate.
Running from the forge was dangerous, but I can see why you did it.
I don’t know where I’m going, but I know I can’t go back to that life. The fire, the chains, the constant pain... I need to find something better, or at least something that isn’t another prison.
I spent my youth as a slave, working in a blacksmith’s forge. The heat and the pain were unbearable, so I ran, hoping to find freedom somewhere beyond the castle walls.
My story? It’s one of anger, rebellion, and the price of defying my family.

I was born into a boyar family, where I was expected to be the perfect, obedient daughter. But I didn’t want that life. I was angry—angry at my parents for trying to control me, for treating me like a puppet. So I did what I could to defy them: I gave my body to every slave, every guard and every boyar!

When they found out, they were furious. They locked me in my room, screamed at me until their voices were hoarse. My mother wept, my father raged. They even called in the priest, thinking I was possessed or cursed. He tried to cleanse me with prayers and rituals, but it did nothing. The anger was still there, burning inside me.

After days of being locked away, I knew I couldn’t stay any longer. I refused to be their prisoner. So one night, I slipped out of the window and ran. I didn’t know where I was going, but anywhere was better than being under their control. I wanted to live my own life, without them dictating my every move.
Defying your parents like that must have taken a lot of courage, even if it meant leaving everything behind.
Running away from your family may have freed you, but it also left you alone in the world.
I don’t know what I’ll do now, but I know I can’t go back. I won’t let them control me, and I won’t live a life they’ve chosen for me. I’ll find my own path, even if it means walking it alone.

I was the daughter of a boyar, but I rebelled against my parents. I gave myself out of anger, and when they tried to control me, I ran away. Now, I’m searching for a life that’s truly mine, far from their influence.
My story? It’s one of laziness, warmth, and a harsh wake-up call after my parents passed away.

I was born to a pair of hard-drinking parents. They didn’t ask much of me, and I didn’t offer much in return. All my life, I spent my days lying on the warm stove, pretending to be ill or sleeping whenever there was work to be done. Why bother when the stove was so comfortable, and there was nothing worth getting up for?

While my parents drank away their days, I lay there, doing nothing, thinking I could live like that forever. But nothing lasts forever. One day, the drink finally took them both, and I was left alone. For the first time in my life, I had to climb down from that stove. I didn’t have a clue what to do.

I tried to survive, but I was hopeless. I had never done anything for myself before. I didn’t know how to work, how to gather food, how to live. So, with no other choice, I left the house and wandered into town, hoping to find someone who could teach me how to survive.
Sounds like you had an easy life—until reality caught up with you.
Learning to survive after doing nothing for so long must have been tough.
I don’t know what I’ll do next, but I know I can’t go back to that old life. The stove is gone, and now I have to figure out how to survive on my own, one day at a time.

I spent my life lying on the warm stove, doing nothing, while my parents drank themselves to death. When they were gone, I had no choice but to leave and try to survive. Now, I’m looking for a way to make it on my own.
Baltic Veteran Horse Skirmisher (Raitas Akščių Žygūnas)
Baltic Elite Horse Skirmisher (Raitas Akščių Viršaitis)

The order was formed from the remnants of the Livonian Brothers of the Sword after their defeat by Samogitians in 1236 at the Battle of Schaulen (Saule). They were incorporated into the Teutonic Order and became known as the Livonian Order in 1237.{newline}{newline}In 1238, the Teutonic Knights of Livonia signed the Treaty of Stensby with the Kingdom of Denmark. Under this agreement, Denmark would support the expansion ambitions of the order in exchange for northern maritime Estonia.{newline}{newline}In 1242, the Livonian Order tried to take the city of Novgorod. However, they were defeated by Alexander Nevsky in the Battle on the Ice.

The Slaven Boyar Group was one of the most influential factions in 13th-century Novgorod, representing the interests of the powerful boyar families from the Slavensky side of the city. Known for their political influence and economic power, the Slaven Boyars played a crucial role in Novgorod's veche (assembly), often advocating for policies that protected the city's autonomy and promoted trade. Their leaders, such as Mikhail Fyodorovich, held key positions, including posadnik (mayor), enabling them to shape Novgorodâ€™s governance and resist external pressures from neighboring princes and foreign powers.

The Zagorodskaya 'Prussian' Boyar Group was a powerful faction within 13th-century Novgorod, associated with the Zagorodsky (Prussian) side of the city. Known for their ties to trade with the Baltic and Prussian regions, this group represented the interests of Novgorod's wealthy merchants and influential boyars who had connections beyond Novgorodâ€™s borders. Led by figures like Posadnik Gavrilo Alekseevich (Gabriel Gorislavich), the Prussian Boyar Group wielded considerable influence within the veche (assembly), shaping Novgorodâ€™s foreign trade policies and contributing to its defense and economic strength.

The Nerev Boyar Group was an influential faction in 13th-century Novgorod, representing the Nerevsky side of the city. This group was comprised of prominent boyar families dedicated to safeguarding Novgorodâ€™s autonomy and managing local governance through the veche (assembly). Known for their strong political voice, the Nerev Boyars were led by powerful figures like Tverdislav Mikhailovich, who played a key role in city politics and in defending Novgorodâ€™s interests against external threats. Their influence was crucial in balancing power among the various factions within Novgorodâ€™s unique republican structure.

The Ludin Boyar Group was a prominent faction in 13th-century Novgorod, representing the Ludin quarter and its influential merchant and boyar families. This group had strong ties to Novgorodâ€™s lucrative trade networks and often advocated for policies that promoted economic growth and protected the cityâ€™s vital commercial interests. Led by respected figures such as Anany Ivanovich, the Ludin Boyars held considerable sway in the veche (assembly), where their focus on trade made them powerful allies and occasional rivals to other boyar factions. Their influence helped shape Novgorodâ€™s economy and maintain its independence as a major trading hub in medieval Rus'.

The Plotnik Boyar Group was a significant faction in 13th-century Novgorod, representing the Plotnik quarter known for its craftsmen, woodworkers, and builders. This group supported Novgorodâ€™s thriving artisan class and often pushed for policies that strengthened local industries and improved infrastructure. Led by figures like Dmitry Stepanovich, the Plotnik Boyars contributed to the cityâ€™s defenses and public works projects, ensuring Novgorod remained fortified and economically stable. Their presence in the veche (assembly) provided a voice for the working class and artisans, balancing the influence of trade-focused and politically oriented factions.

The Ladoga Boyar Group was a powerful faction associated with Ladoga, a strategically important town within the Novgorod Republic in the 13th century. Positioned along key trade routes connecting Novgorod to the Baltic Sea and surrounding regions, Ladoga was crucial for trade and defense. The Ladoga Boyar Group was led by a namestnik (deputy or governor) appointed by Novgorod, such as Vasily Borisovich, who oversaw the townâ€™s administration, defense, and tax collection. This group played a vital role in safeguarding Novgorod's northern interests and ensuring control over regional trade, balancing local autonomy with loyalty to the Novgorod veche (assembly).

The Pskov Veche Council was the governing body of Pskov in the 13th century, providing a unique blend of local autonomy under the influence of the Novgorod Republic. The council was made up of prominent boyars and local leaders who represented the interests of Pskovâ€™s citizens in matters of trade, defense, and diplomacy. While Novgorod often sent figurehead rulers, such as Vasilii Aleksandrovich, the son of Alexander Nevsky, the real power lay with the Pskov Veche Council. This assembly safeguarded Pskovâ€™s independence within the framework of Novgorodâ€™s authority, making decisions to protect its economic and political interests in the face of regional challenges.

The Luki Boyar Council was the governing body in Luki during the 13th century, a town under the Novgorod Republic's influence. Due to its strategic location along trade and military routes, the Luki Boyar Council was primarily focused on maintaining local defense and managing trade. The council was led by a namestnik (deputy or governor) appointed by Novgorod, such as Andrei Mikhailovich, who oversaw the townâ€™s affairs, ensuring loyalty to Novgorod while addressing local needs. This councilâ€™s leadership contributed to the stability and prosperity of Luki, balancing the interests of Novgorod with the town's unique regional significance.

The Torzhok Ruling Boyars were the governing group in Torzhok during the 13th century, a vital trade town within the Novgorod Republic. Positioned along key trade routes between Novgorod and central Rus' territories, Torzhok served as a critical economic and defensive outpost. The ruling boyars, led by a namestnik (deputy) appointed by Novgorod, such as Ivan Svyatoslavich, managed trade, fortified defenses, and ensured local stability. While loyal to Novgorodâ€™s veche (assembly), the Torzhok Ruling Boyars wielded considerable autonomy, balancing local governance with the interests of the republic and maintaining Torzhokâ€™s role as a regional hub for commerce and protection.

The Sobiesławice clan, also known as the House of Sobiesław (Samborides), was the ruling dynasty of Pomerelia (Eastern Pomerania, including Gdańsk) in the mid-13th century. The dynasty maintained independence from Polish Piast rulers, engaged in conflicts with the Teutonic Order and Greater Poland, and governed through a network of fortified settlements and coastal trade hubs.

The Święcowie clan (House of Święca) was one of the most influential noble families in Pomerelia in the mid-13th century, holding key administrative positions under the Samboride rulers. Initially loyal to Duke Świętopełk II, they later aligned with Sambor II and the Teutonic Order, playing a crucial role in the region's shifting power dynamics.

The Ogończyk clan was a prominent Polish noble family in the mid-13th century, with strong ties to Pomerelia and Kuyavia, often serving as knights and castellans under the Piast and Samboride rulers. Known for their military service and land holdings, they played a role in regional conflicts, sometimes aligning with the Piasts of Greater Poland against Pomerelian independence.

The Piasts of Masovia were a powerful ruling dynasty in the mid-13th century, governing the Duchy of Masovia under Duke Siemowit I. They focused on expanding their territory, securing Masovia’s borders against the Yotvingians and Lithuanians, and maintaining autonomy from the Polish Crown, while also engaging in alliances and conflicts with neighboring Piast rulers.

The Piasts of Kuyavia were a ruling branch of the Piast dynasty, governing Kuyavia in the mid-13th century under Duke Casimir I of Kuyavia. They were involved in dynastic struggles with the Piasts of Greater Poland and Masovia, while also facing external threats from the Teutonic Order and Prussian tribes, shaping the region’s political landscape.

The Kurowie clan was an influential noble family in Masovia in the mid-13th century, known for their land holdings and service to the Piast dukes. They played key roles in local governance and military affairs, with ties to the Masovian ducal court.

The Kossakowski clan was an emerging noble family in Masovia in the mid-13th century, with roots in Ciechanów County and connections to local Piast rulers. They later became influential landowners and military leaders, playing a role in the political affairs of Masovia and the Grand Duchy of Lithuania.

The Chronicle of Henry of Livonia mentions the Selonians at the beginning of the 13th century, when they were conquered and christened. The author of the chronicle describes the Selonians as Lithuanian allies. Their lands were subjects of the principalities of Jersika and Koknese, which were vassals of the principality of Polotsk. The Southern lands however were ruled by Lithuanian lords.

The Latgalians are an Eastern Baltic tribe whose origin is little known. In the 5th and 6th centuries, they lived in the west of the Aiviekste River, and later on in nearly all the territory of that region. In the first two decades of the 13th century, the Western Latgalians allied with German (mainly Saxon) crusaders. Their lands (the Eldership of Tālava, the Principality of Jersika and the Principality of Koknese) were incorporated into Livonia as vassal states. In the 11th century, Eastern Orthodoxy started to spread in Latgalian lands from Polotsk and Pskov. In the 12th century, Latgalian lands and their rulers paid tribute to the dukes of Polotsk. During the Livonian crusade in the 13th century, Latgalian elders switched from Eastern Orthodoxy to Roman Catholicism and became vassals of the Livonian Order.

The Livonians referred to themselves as rāndalist - 'coast dwellers' and supported themselves mainly by fishing, but also by agriculture and animal husbandry. Since they controlled an important trade route, the Daugava River, their culture was highly developed through trade with the Gotlanders, Rus and Finns, and, from the end of the first millennium AD onwards, with the Germans, Swedes and Danes. During the Livonian Crusade, once prosperous Livonia was devastated, and whole regions were almost completely depopulated. This vacuum was filled by Curonians, Semigallians, Latgallians and Selonians – who started to move into the area around 1220, and continued to do so for at least thirty years.

On the eve of Northern Crusades, the people then residing in Saaremaa(Ösel) were described in the Livonian Rhymed Chronicle: The Oeselians, neighbors to the Kurs (Curonians), are surrounded by the sea and never fear strong armies as their strength is in their ships. In summers when they can travel across the sea they oppress the surrounding lands by raiding both Christians and pagans

In the 13th century, the Ushkuiniki were a group of Russian river pirates and raiders primarily composed of Novgorodians. They were skilled in navigating the river systems of Northern and Eastern Europe, particularly using ushkuis—small, agile boats ideal for navigating rivers and shallow waters.{newline}{newline}The Ushkuiniki raided far beyond Novgorod's borders, targeting neighboring principalities, trade centers, and even foreign territories, including lands of the Volga Bulgars and territories along the White Sea. Their raids often served both economic and strategic purposes, supplying Novgorod with goods and wealth, while also extending its influence and control over the river trade routes.{newline}{newline}Unlike typical pirates, the Ushkuiniki sometimes operated with the tacit approval or outright support of Novgorod's authorities, who saw their raids as a way to expand trade dominance and keep regional rivals in check. They played a key role in establishing Novgorod's dominance over river trade and securing its economic interests during the 13th century.

King Mindaugas of Lithuania is the revered first king of Lithuania, known for his strategic acumen and diplomatic skill in uniting the Lithuanian tribes under a single banner in 1253. As of 1259, he continues to strengthen his realm through both alliances and conquests, working towards the consolidation of his kingdom and the expansion of its influence across Eastern Europe.

Morta is Queen of Lithuania upon her husband King Mindaugas's accession. She is Mindaugas' second wife. He killed her first husband Vismantas from the Bulaičiai family in the power struggle in 1251. Morta is a capable woman who advises her husband in political affairs and is a fierce defender of Western Christianity.

The Kingdom of Lithuania exists from 1251. King Mindaugas is the first chieftain crowned as King of Lithuania with the Pope's assent. The formation of the Kingdom of Lithuania represents a partially successful attempt at unifying all surrounding Baltic tribes into a single state.

The Teutonic Order is a Catholic religious institution founded as a military society in 1190 in Acre, Kingdom of Jerusalem. It is the leading power of The Northern Crusades or Baltic Crusades - colonization and Christianization campaigns undertaken by Catholic Christian military orders and kingdoms, primarily against the pagan Baltic, Finnic and West Slavic peoples around the southern and eastern shores of the Baltic Sea, and also against Orthodox Christian Slavs.

Prussia is a loose alliance of pagan Prussian tribes with similar languages and cultures. Prussian tribes are organized in a loose confederation led by local chieftains. Their society is largely tribal and clan-based, with leaders known as 'kriwe' or 'kriwes' who hold both religious and political authority. These leaders are supported by a council of nobles or elders. The Prussian tribes do not have a centralized state structure, and their political organization are more focused on local governance and tribal coalitions, which often shifted alliances and rivalries.
Baltic Tribes is a loose alliance of pagan baltic tribes with similar languages and cultures.

The conquest of Northern Estonia, culminating in the establishment of Danish rule in 1219, was achieved under King Valdemar II of Denmark, known as Valdemar the Victorious. This significant event took place during the Northern Crusades, a period characterized by the Christian states of Northern Europe launching military campaigns against the pagan tribes of the Baltic region. The pivotal moment occurred at the Battle of Lindanise, on June 15, 1219, where Danish forces decisively defeated the Estonian tribes.{newline}{newline}The battle is famously noted for the legendary appearance of the Dannebrog, the flag of Denmark, which is said to have fallen from the skies during a critical point in the battle, boosting the morale of the Danish troops and leading to their victory. {newline}{newline}This victory not only solidified Danish influence in Estonia but also marked the beginning of significant Christianization and the establishment of feudal structures throughout the region. Under Danish rule, Reval was fortified and developed into a major center of commerce and governance, integrating Northern Estonia more closely into the broader European economic and cultural sphere.

From the second half of the 11th century vasal-union relations began to form between Połack and Lithuania. The reason for consolidation was a common enemy – Kievan Rus. Initially Połack played a leading role. But as time went on, Lithuania took that place. In 1259, thanks to a dynastic marriage, the Lithuanian prince Tautvilas ruled in Połack. The Połack principalities became vassal princedoms, fought with Lithuania against common enemies: Golden Horde and Teutonic Order, but were not yet part of Lithuania. They had high autonomy, and many Połack princes fought for the main throne, Połack, among themselves and external enemies, including Lithuania.

The Novgorod Republic in the 13th century was a unique and powerful medieval state in northern Rus', known for its republican-style governance and economic prosperity. Unlike other principalities, Novgorod operated under a decentralized system, with real power held by the veche (popular assembly), representing the interests of local boyars, merchants, and citizens. Key offices, including the posadnik (mayor), tysyatsky (military leader), and archbishop, managed the cityâ€™s administration, defense, and church affairs.{newline}{newline}Novgorod maintained semi-autonomy within the broader Rus' political sphere, balancing relations with the Grand Princes of Vladimir and the Mongol Empire. Known as a major trading hub, Novgorodâ€™s wealth and influence came from its extensive connections with the Baltic Sea, the Hanseatic League, and Eastern markets. Its strategic location allowed Novgorod to flourish, blending self-governance, economic strength, and diplomatic skill to navigate the challenges of the 13th century.

In the mid-13th century, Masovia was ruled by Duke Siemowit I of the Piast dynasty, who sought to defend and expand his duchy amid conflicts with neighboring Polish and Baltic powers. The region faced frequent raids from the Yotvingians and Lithuanians, while Masovian nobles played a key role in the political struggles between the Piasts of Greater Poland and Kuyavia.

In the mid-13th century, Pomerania was divided between Western Pomerania (Duchy of Pomerania, ruled by the Griffins) and Eastern Pomerania (Pomerelia, ruled by the Sobiesławice dynasty). While Western Pomerania remained loosely tied to the Holy Roman Empire, Pomerelia was engaged in power struggles with the Piasts of Poland, the Teutonic Order, and local noble clans over control of Gdańsk and strategic trade routes.

Baltic Paganism is the pre-Christian religion practiced by the Baltic peoples, including Lithuanians, Latvians, and Prussians. It was characterized by the worship of natural forces, ancestors, and a pantheon of deities, such as PerkÅ«nas (god of thunder) and Laima (goddess of fate). Rituals often took place in sacred groves, and the religion emphasized harmony with nature, seasonal cycles, and community traditions. Despite the spread of Christianity in the region during the Middle Ages, elements of Baltic paganism persisted for centuries.

Catholicism is a major branch of Christianity that originated in the Roman Empire and is centered around the teachings of Jesus Christ as interpreted by the Roman Catholic Church. It emphasizes the sacraments, particularly the Eucharist, and the authority of the Pope as the spiritual leader. Catholicism is known for its rich traditions, rituals, and veneration of saints. In medieval Europe, the Catholic Church played a significant role in daily life, politics, education, and culture, guiding the spiritual and moral values of its followers.

Orthodoxy is a branch of Christianity that developed in the Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire, distinguishing itself through its theological emphasis, liturgical traditions, and practices. Centered on the teachings of Jesus Christ, Orthodoxy places importance on the sacraments, the veneration of icons, and maintaining the traditions of the early Church Fathers. The Orthodox Church is organized into a collection of self-governing churches, each led by a bishop or patriarch, without a central papal figure. It has a rich liturgical life, characterized by elaborate rituals, chants, and a strong sense of community and spiritual continuity.

Rus' culture, notable in Eastern Europe, blends Slavic traditions with influences from neighboring regions. It encompasses city-states like Kiev, Novgorod, and Vladimir, each governed by a prince. The society is hierarchically structured with princes, nobles, free peasants, and servants. Predominantly Eastern Orthodox since Prince Vladimir's Christianization in 988, Rus' culture aligns closely with Byzantium, contrasting with Western Catholic and Baltic pagan customs.

The Balts, who live along the southeastern Baltic Sea, have their own languages, unique cultural practices, and pagan beliefs. They organize themselves into tribes, each led by a chieftain, maintaining independence while sharing a common cultural and religious bond.
The Northern Crusaders are a group of Teutonic Knights who embarked on military campaigns to Christianize the Baltic people, leading to significant cultural and territorial changes in the region.

Danish culture, marked by a strong monarchical system, deep religious fervor, and a legacy of Viking exploration, drove its participation in the Northern Crusades and its territorial expansion.

In the 13th century, the Nadruvians were a Baltic tribe inhabiting the region of Nadruva, characterized by a decentralized tribal society, steadfast pagan traditions, and determined resistance against crusader incursions.

Polish culture in the 13th century combined Christian religious traditions with Slavic customs, centered around wooden and stone churches, castles, and monasteries. Due to the feudal fragmentation (period of division into duchies), Poland was politically divided among Piast dynasty princes, yet maintained cultural unity through shared religious practices and traditions.
My story? It’s the weight of a spindle in my hands and the feeling of raw wool between my fingers.

I was born to a weaver’s family, where every day was spent at the loom. From the moment I could sit upright, my mother taught me to spin wool, to dye it, to weave it into cloth that would be sold at the market. It was honest work, but it left little room for dreams.

The loom bound my fate as surely as it wove the threads of fabric. I watched my older sisters marry men chosen for them, men who cared little for love and more for the dowries our father promised. I knew my turn would come soon, my future already decided before I could speak against it.

I refused to be traded like a bolt of cloth. On the night before my betrothal, I took my mother’s cloak and what little coin I had and fled. I didn’t know where I was going—only that I needed to go somewhere beyond the loom, beyond the small room where I had spent my whole life.
A life of weaving and duty… it’s not surprising you sought something more.
Running from a fate you never chose… that takes courage.

I couldn’t stay. My hands ached for something other than the feel of wool and thread. Now I wander, searching for a life where I can make my own choices, where I am more than just another daughter to be wed off.
I was raised as a weaver’s daughter, expected to marry and continue the cycle. But I wanted more. I left, searching for a life beyond the loom and the threads of fate woven for me.
My story? It’s the weight of the plow on my shoulders and the endless stretch of fields under the sky.

I was born in a small village nestled between the forests and fields. My father was a farmer, and from the moment I could walk, I was put to work in the fields. The land was both our livelihood and our curse—droughts, storms, and the lord’s taxes left us with barely enough to survive.

The village was my whole world, but I always felt the pull of the road. Traders came with stories of distant towns, knights passing through spoke of wars and glory. I dreamt of seeing Kraków, of walking through its grand streets instead of the same muddy paths I’d known all my life.

When my father died, there was nothing keeping me there. The land would go to my older brother, and I refused to spend my days toiling under another’s orders. I took what little I had and left, hoping to find a new life beyond the fields.
The land can be harsh, but it’s all many people have ever known.
Leaving behind the life of a farmer isn’t easy, but the road holds its own challenges.
I left behind the farm, the village, and the weight of my father’s expectations. Now I wander, searching for a place where I can be more than just another son of the soil.
I was raised on a farm, where every day was a battle against the earth and the seasons. But I wanted more than that life. Now, I travel in search of a future beyond the fields.
